8. Service Account Authentication with Compute Viewer Role
Create a service account with “Compute Viewer” permissions and attach it to a virtual
machine to enable secure service-to- service authentication.
Activity 4: Essential Google Cloud Infrastructure: Core Services
Lab: Cloud storage, Lesson: Roles


✅ PART A: Service Account Authentication (Compute Viewer Role)

👉 (This is what your question title asks)

🎯 Goal:

Create a Service Account → assign Compute Viewer → attach to VM

✅ Step 1: Create Service Account
Go to ☰ Navigation Menu
Click IAM & Admin → Service Accounts
Click ➕ Create Service Account

Fill:

Name → compute-viewer-sa

Click:
👉 Create and Continue

✅ Step 2: Assign Role
In Select Role
Choose:
Compute Engine → Compute Viewer

👉 Click Continue → Done

✅ Step 3: Create VM and Attach Service Account
Go to Compute Engine → VM Instances
Click Create Instance

Fill:

Name → vm-sa-demo
Machine → e2-micro
OS → Debian 12
🔐 Attach Service Account
Scroll to Security
In Service Account dropdown
→ Select compute-viewer-sa
Access scopes:
→ Select Allow full access to all APIs (or set specific if required)

👉 Click Create

✅ Step 4: Test Authentication
Click SSH on VM

Run:

gcloud compute instances list

👉 ✅ Works (because Compute Viewer role)

❌ Try restricted action:
gcloud compute instances delete vm-sa-demo

👉 ❌ Fails (Viewer role cannot delete)

🎯 Result:

✔ Secure service-to-service authentication
✔ VM uses service account instead of user credentials
✔ Least privilege applied

✅ PART B: Cloud Storage Lab (Full Step-by-Step)

👉 (This is the long lab you pasted)

🔹 TASK 1: Create Bucket
Go to Cloud Storage → Buckets
Click Create

Fill:

Bucket name → unique (ex: mybucket123)
Location → Region
Access → Fine-grained
Uncheck public access prevention

👉 Click Create

🔹 TASK 2: Cloud Shell Setup
Click Activate Cloud Shell
export BUCKET_NAME_1=your-bucket-name
echo $BUCKET_NAME_1
Download sample file
curl https://hadoop.apache.org/docs/current/hadoop-project-dist/hadoop-common/ClusterSetup.html > setup.html
Create copies
cp setup.html setup2.html
cp setup.html setup3.html
🔹 TASK 3: ACL (Access Control List)
Upload file
gcloud storage cp setup.html gs://$BUCKET_NAME_1/
Check ACL
gsutil acl get gs://$BUCKET_NAME_1/setup.html
Make private
gsutil acl set private gs://$BUCKET_NAME_1/setup.html
Make public
gsutil acl ch -u AllUsers:R gs://$BUCKET_NAME_1/setup.html
🔹 TASK 4: Customer-Supplied Encryption Key (CSEK)
Generate key
python3 -c 'import base64,os; print(base64.encodebytes(os.urandom(32)))'

👉 Copy key (remove b'')

Edit config
nano .boto

Add:

encryption_key=YOUR_KEY
Upload encrypted files
gsutil cp setup2.html gs://$BUCKET_NAME_1/
gsutil cp setup3.html gs://$BUCKET_NAME_1/
🔹 TASK 5: Rotate Keys
Move key to decrypt
nano .boto

Change:

# encryption_key=old
decryption_key1=old
Generate new key and add:
encryption_key=new_key
Rewrite file
gsutil rewrite -k gs://$BUCKET_NAME_1/setup2.html
🔹 TASK 6: Lifecycle Policy
Create file
nano life.json

Paste:

{
  "rule": [
    {
      "action": {"type": "Delete"},
      "condition": {"age": 31}
    }
  ]
}
Apply
gsutil lifecycle set life.json gs://$BUCKET_NAME_1
🔹 TASK 7: Enable Versioning
gsutil versioning set on gs://$BUCKET_NAME_1
Upload versions
gcloud storage cp -v setup.html gs://$BUCKET_NAME_1
List versions
gcloud storage ls -a gs://$BUCKET_NAME_1/setup.html
Restore old version
gcloud storage cp VERSION_NAME recovered.txt
🔹 TASK 8: Directory Sync
Create folders
mkdir firstlevel
mkdir firstlevel/secondlevel
cp setup.html firstlevel
cp setup.html firstlevel/secondlevel
Sync
gsutil rsync -r ./firstlevel gs://$BUCKET_NAME_1/firstlevel
